review:
While there are many interesting changes to gameplay and some new mechanics including a vastly different combat system, the game in its current state does not deserve attention to the same degree as the first one. I played an enormous amount of hours in this game and have a good grasp on its mechanics, issues, and advantages. Sadly, the former dramatically outweigh the latter. I still cannot justify the price jump due to the game being quite similar to the first one with less than enough content to justify the price increase.

Below, I will try to list both pros and cons in comparison to the first entry in the series and in general.

Here are positives:
- an improved crafting/research system;
- itemization is slightly more interesting in theory yet lacks diversity and there is seemingly no room for improvement;
- exploration is also improved compared to Thea: The Awakening;
- more art and fancy imagery added (hardly a meaningful improvement).

Here are negatives:
- the story is fine yet the storytelling itself is so reminiscent of the first game that I didn't feel that it was improved;
- the combat system is boring and lacks interesting mechanics;
- the interface is an utter mess that requires too many actions and lacks tooltips (the latter may be improved);
- the performance is a big issue as the game "eats" up to 6GB of ram for no apparent reason;
- the AI is lucklaster which is detrimental due to a poor and rigid combat system;
- the AI responsible for auto-resolving battles is impossible, as devs mentioned, to improve drastically due to possible performance drops if battles were to be played in the background;
- the game feels very clunky and slow not only due to poor optimization but also because of some gameplay mechanics.

The main issue I personally have with the game and why I think the interest is slowly diminishing from one patch to another with very small yet noticeable dips in concurrent active players is that pacing of the game is just off and I do not see how it could be improved. The amount of micromanagement and unnecessary clicking/dragging is just awful. The interface forces you to go through countless screens in order to get to what you need to do and you have to do it repeatedly.

The game does not present anything in terms of endgame. There are dozens of cheeses and gameplay mechanics that significantly affect the ability of devs to balance the game and bring more complexity/challenge to players. New mechanics like seasons, research, and... I don't even know what is truly "new"... they just seem underwhelming. I just can't be excited for such insignificant mechanics that barely affect how you play the game.

Now, the amount of hours I invested in this game is mostly due to me checking out new patches and changes. Thea 2 basically made me switch to it from the Awakening and I didn't find anything meaningful and, more importantly, worth the price. It is absolutely not a game for people who didn't like the first game. It is not a game that I would recommend to any of my friends. It is not a game that promises to grow into something memorable. I hoped that it would become the "They Are Billions" of turn-based adventure games. I hoped that Thea 2 would be something close to the "King's Bounty" series. Sadly, none of my hopes materialized.

I bet that there will be many people who will love the work of MuHa Games. I've seen many passionate people on their forum and in discussions. However, it is a community that I won't be a part of and won't invite any of my friends to.

P.S. The roadmap is mostly done. Minor tweaks and changes won't make any meaningful difference. I think this is my final review of the product and not going to play it anymore.

A pity for the sequel; 
Still if you didnot play, go buy Thea ; i also bought it to PS4 for supporting, it was one of the best games ever made;
But here they changed combat system while there is no need; and didnot change other silly things like ombat was the problem; and that silly combat system also forces computers , 
